In particular, they were able to isolate two different isotopes of Radium: Radon's daughter isotope, which has an atomic mass of approximately 226 units, and another isotope with an atomic mass of about 228 units.

The Curies' discovery of Radium was a significant breakthrough in the field of radioactivity. They shared the Nobel Prize in Physics for this work in 1903, along with Antoine Henri Becquerel.

Other scientists have since isolated additional isotopes of Radium, including Radium-223 and Radium-224.
